He propped himself on his left elbow and reached to his right side, feeling his wait where a long slit in his skin was showing with a dull red outline. He took a breath and the pain felt like a knife stabbing him. He let out a small cry of pain, drawing the attention of a fisherman. The man walked in, a curious look upon his face.<br>
&quot;You are lucky,&quot; said the man, &quot;Most who suffered such wounds would now face their hereafter if it would receive them.&quot;<br>
&quot;Where am I?&quot; asked the man.<br>
&quot;You are in the southern desert, in the Oasis Sir Knight.&quot; Was the reply.<br>
&quot;Knight?&quot; he said, shaking his head.<br>
He had no memory. But now images returned and he began to recall small flashes. <br>
&quot;Who am I?&quot; He asked.<br>
&quot;Your name is either Donlan or Donnely,&quot; the man said, pointing to a breastplate. &quot;It is written in your armor, but damned if I can read well. Still, you are a lucky sort and don’t you go abouts runnin for a while. There be strange folk in these parts and you best wait till you can breathe better.&quot;<br>
&quot;Donnely,&quot; he said, &quot;yes, that is my name. Donnely McLeod. Where did you find me?&quot;<br>
&quot;Well,&quot; said the man, &quot;You seemed to find me, stumblin around and such into my camp here. Why you was lucky to find me home at the time; otherwise I woulda not been able to clean up your wound there.&quot;<br>
&quot;I offer my thanks,&quot; Donnely said, &quot;And I will repay you one day.&quot;<br>
&quot;No worries master,&quot; said the fisherman smiling, &quot;You just keep to your bed and this will be all in my care.&quot;<br>
Donnely thanked the odd man and drifted back to sleep. He began to have strange dreams that troubled his soul and they came to frighten him. But as soon as he woke, the memory was gone and only the fear remained. For several days he was cooped up and rarely ever saw the fisherman. After a week he felt he was strong enough to walk so he made his way outside the hut.<br>
The air was hot. The sun and sand were hot and even the trees were hot. Donnely hated the desert. He would travel for an extra week just to bypass the sand and the heat by way of the grasslands. All he now wore was a pair of leggings and a necklace with a symbol with a sword and three stars; the symbol of Marr and priesthood as a Paladin. He thought for a moment and his memory flooded back.<br>
His life was a glorious battle and he was a great commander. Armies had flocked to his banner in defiance of the Militia. He was ousted from the order after the cold blooded murder of a young man who spoke against Marr in a vain attempt to defend the Militia's actions. He felt his eyes grow angry upon that memory. But it was his life. <br>
His entire life was war and war without end. He had killed hundreds and when he had his army he killed thousands. He felt no pity for the young man. His heart was always trying to do good, but there had always been a black spot that infected him somehow. He lowered his head and sighed.<br>
&quot;Well hello kind master!&quot; said the fisherman as he walked up with a net, &quot;I see you be feelin better now? Well that’s lovely! I might want ta warn ya of the storm comin though. A big dry storm that whips up the sand somethin furious and you might not want to be here when it hits.&quot;<br>
&quot;Where do you go?&quot; asked Donnely.<br>
&quot;Well, there're some folks down further the lake that let ya stay in their inn if you pay a penny or so, not much mind you at least, but the walls are made of wood and stone so it’s a good place to bunker down should it get to bad.&quot;<br>
&quot;Thank you,&quot; began Donnely, &quot;I shall heed your words if I may. How long till the storm reaches?&quot;<br>
&quot;Few hours at the most.&quot; Said the fisherman, who now turned and began walking down the lakeside, &quot;You may want to hurry!&quot;<br>
His voice trailed off and Donnely stood for a moment. He rubbed his mustache and turned into the hut, pulling his tunic on and inspecting his ruined breastplate. There was a gash in the right side, mad by a small axe. He pulled the plate over his chest and connected the back plate. He donned the rest of his armor and found that he had no sword.<br>
He cursed and remembered it dropping in the sand somewhere. He moved out of the inn and moved to the door. Suddenly he stopped. He ducked behind the wall of the hut, hearing murmuring and feet walking in the sand. The murmur was a chant of sorts, and across his path there walked six stragglers, weather beaten, with torn clothes and mean faces. Donnely cursed to himself for loosing his blade.<br>
They walked to the edge of the water. Donnely stepped out and they turned to look at him. They ignored him and went back to their ritual. They fell to their knees and bowed to the lake. Donnely looked out across the lake and his riddle was answered. They bowed, not to the lake, but to a tall tower, covered in vine and standing solitaire upon a stone mount that rose forty feet from the lake. The tower itself was over a hundred at least.<br>
&quot;They watch them,&quot; said a voice.<br>
Donnely turned and saw a young man standing behind him, looking at the wandering, ragged band who now bowed.<br>
&quot;They call upon his thoughts to strengthen their powers so that they may take what they need from us. They will not heed you or see you until he tells them to.&quot;<br>
&quot;Who might that be?&quot; asked Donnely.<br>
The young man laughed for a moment then spoke, &quot;Their god. They have left their own path and go mad in his service. I speak of Innoruk.&quot;<br>
&quot;Ah,&quot; said Donnely laughing, &quot;A fake, heathen religion that only requires ignorance to become its scribe or elder.&quot;<br>
&quot;You have not been here before good Sir Knight.&quot; Said the stranger, &quot;And I shall show you what we do to them.&quot;<br>
Two more young men sprang from behind two thick palms and drew broad swords. One found the leader of the group and dispatched his head quickly. The blood spattered across the face of the next one, who stood and drew a sword to defend. His bowels were split open and his innards fell onto the ground from a quick slice. The talkative young man had swung a small tulwar and split him across the belly.<br>
Donnely was enraged. He grabbed one of the young men and smashed his gauntlet into his face, breaking his nose and causing him to sleep well. He grabbed the sword and began to defend the heathens, who still knelt.<br>
&quot;I cannot allow you to do this!&quot; he shouted.<br>
&quot;They wish it Sir McLeod!&quot; said the man. &quot;And you shall also when Innoruk blesses you with death to his realm!&quot;<br>
At that the young man threw back his robe and his body seemed to shred like paper as a new form pulsated inside him. Donnely watched for a moment and then turned, running down the slope of the lake. He ran for a long while until he came to the inn that the fisherman had spoke of.<br>
&quot;Kind sir!&quot; he shouted, &quot;Please let me in. I have mush money and will gladly repay you!&quot;<br>
The door opened and an old man welcomed him in. He walked to a room and found the fisherman. He told him of the experience and waited for his response.<br>
&quot;Well,&quot; said the old man, &quot;It happens every storm. That is why I leave to here before the troubles be startin up there.&quot;<br>
&quot;Then I shall wait here also,&quot; said Donnely.<br>
&quot;You mustn't, &quot;Said the fisherman.<br>
&quot;Why not?! Am I to be slain by the lunatics that inhabit these parts?&quot; shouted Donnely.<br>
&quot;You must not bring peril to us!&quot; Said the fisherman, now standing, his old demeanor fading, &quot;They are the servants of Innoruk! They will die in his service and wish only to feed his fast halls with souls every day!&quot;<br>
Donnely backed out of the door and ran from the inn. His heart raced and the wind began to howl. He did not know where he could run. Every step became harder to fulfill as the sand began to blast against him. The he began to feel a presence. He spun round, his eyes stinging from the sand. It was one of the young men, but he was hooded.<br>
Donnely drew the short blade that he had taken and watched the man stumble through the wind and sand to reach him. Now the wind was literally knocking him over; sand filled the joints of his armor as he tried to maintain his footing. Visibility was only a few feet, but the dark shadow of the cloaked figure drew closer. Then he came into sight.<br>
The figure looked slightly contorted, not moving but now stood oddly in the wind. Then there was a sound a bow snap and an arrow glanced off Donnely's arm. He dug into the ground and pulled the arrow up. He mustered all his strength and leapt towards the attacker who was loading another arrow to loose at him. But the man never drew.<br>
Donnely jumped on him and plunged the arrow deep in his eye. As Donnely did so he saw the dark skin and the pointed ear. It was a Tier'dal. The elf screamed loudly as Donnely pushed the arrow deeper and deeper in. Dark blood spattered from the wound, but he held on as the elf twisted and cried out. Donnely closed his eyes, trying to drown out the scream with a thought. He held the arrow firmly and kept stabbing deeper and deeper until the figure only shivered.<br>
He pulled out the short sword and aimed it for the heart, stabbing through boiled leather and cloth. It silenced the moaning elf and gave peace to Donnely. He stood, the sand searing his skin and burying his feet. But it was not over. He could see two more of the figures coming towards him. But behind them there was a more sinister shape.<br>
Suddenly, one of the men was lifted into the air. Donnely watched as his neck and left arm were separated from the rest of his body. There was a short scream and the other figure turned to see the grim shadow. But he wailed and screamed, falling to his knees and bowing. The long, slicing edge, swung down and pierced his spine, jutting out from his stomach below.<br>
Then the shadow came to Donnely. He turned and stumbled through the sand and ran for the palms that lined the lake. He fell down the lakeside and felt the cool touch of water. The sand still blew, but not as hard because of the steep embankment. He stayed cuddled there for a few minutes, seeing if he could hide from the foul demon. It seemed to work.<br>
An hour later he found himself waking. Finally, he gathered the strength to move and stood. The sandstorm had moved on and only a light breeze carried a thin layer of sand across the dunes now. Donnely crawled from the lakeside and made his way east, back towards the inn. Standing on its doorstep were a few men, including the fisherman.<br>
&quot;You!&quot; he shouted as the fisherman turned, &quot;Has all sanity fled my mind? Where is the grim specter of death that has tormented my soul these days?&quot;<br>
&quot;My, my,&quot; said the man, &quot;You truly are the lucky one. First an axe and now a sandstorm you have survived. And the specter of death you speak of is where you found him.&quot;<br>
&quot;Speak!&quot; Said Donnely as he strode up to the man, &quot;I have killed men and many men in my life. Where is death, but that I should wait for it and know it. For everywhere I go I leave death behind! What is this that has followed me and questioned my very sanity?&quot;<br>
The fisherman smiled, &quot;You have not believed had you good sir knight? You have never seen the foul beast that that this world has. There are terrors in this land that you know not. Terrors as wondrous and deadly… and yet you cannot believe.&quot;<br>
Donnely thought for a moment, &quot;How is it… How can it be that I was so blind? You have tricked me somehow into the truth.&quot;<br>
Donnely finally lost all his strength and fell to his knees. Blackness robbed him of conciseness as he fell to the ground. He was taken inside the inn and there they lay him upon a bed. For ages he slept, his head now peaceful and the frightful dreams gone. <br>
He woke later, his armor had been polished clean of sand and beside him lay a long blanket that was wrapped around something. It was long; five feet perhaps, but he knew that it was a sword. He opened up the gift. On the blade was a symbol… It had a sword and three stars, symbolizing Mithaniel Marr. He looked around and found that he was no longer in the inn. He was in a stone room of marble and he could hear the soft trickle of water. <br>
He felt now refreshed after his ordeals and stood, his bones cracking from sleep. He stretched and stood. He wore only a red kilt and a white shirt. He looked around for more clothes, but was unsuccessful in locating any. He walked out of the room into a larger room that was illuminated by a pale blue light. He walked over to a stone railing and bent over, surprised to find the bottom almost a hundred feet below. <br>
He suddenly realized where he was. This was the Temple of Mithaniel Marr. It was where the priest resided during their training. He walked back into his room and found a large stone door. He walked outside and felt the cool air of his home. He took a deep breath, but then he began to wonder on how he had arrived here.<br>
The voice of a greatly aged man came from behind him, &quot;The sleeping knight has awoken.&quot;<br>
&quot;Who are you?&quot; asked Donnely, not seeing any particular robe of rank on the man. &quot;How is it that I have come to this place?&quot;<br>
&quot;Do you not know me?&quot; said the immensely old man laughing lightly, &quot;Or has your head not ever healed?&quot;<br>
&quot;You!&quot; Donnely said shocked. &quot;The fisherman! How come you to be so old?!&quot;<br>
&quot;Time has passed,&quot; he said kindly, &quot;And you have now awoken to a new world. You fell into deep sleep and everything around you has become what it is now. Why, even the Militia have ceased such open war against us now, but it was a heavy price to pay to try and bring you here. Still, you have come and now you have awoken.<br>
&quot;Go now to the halls of Valeron Dunshire and there he will give you leave… or perhaps more. But in any case you have a new life, for in this you can be a new person perhaps.&quot;<br>
Donnely sat on his bed. He hung his head and sighed. He looked up to thank the old man, but he was gone. Donnely went back to the terrace, but no sight of the old man was found. He ran to the large room and looked, but the man had utterly vanished. Donnely put a hand to his head and felt the rays of the sun stream in his room through the open door. He stood and left the room.<br>
Standing on the terrace he watched the gardens; birds and squirrels and grass that moved slightly with the wind. He lost himself in deep thought and began to wonder about what he was. All things that were… had gone. He smiled and took a deep breath of air. Perhaps now he would find the peace in his mind he had so wished for his entire life.<br>
But there was a sinister shadow that lurked in the world and he turned his gaze south towards that dreaded temple in the desert. He was once a great knight and now he would return to his duty. He turned into his room and did not return to the terrace. Instead he left the temple and headed through the streets of North Freeport, his steps finding the path back to the place where he had once been disgraced. <p>"Bleating and babbling I fell on his neck with a scream.
