<br>
The morning of the excursion came, and it was quite like any others.  Drakhnar packed the supplies he would need, some bloodwater, a few bags of earthworm munch and some dried froglok legs, and his supply of bone chips.  He then set out to meet Elder Trassk.  Drakhnar found him deep in meditation atop the stump of a long since toppled, once great, granite pillar in what was now refered to as the &quot;Field of Bone&quot;.  No sooner had he arrived when the old necromancer decended from his perch and motioned for the youthfull necromancer to follow.  Drakhnar followed the aged lizard out accross the long dead resivior that his peers called, &quot;the pit&quot;.  It was a short walk to the Tower itself but it was not an easy one.  Drakhnar and the old necro had to be carefull of the various outcast Iksars that roamed the area.  However those few fools that did cross their path were quickly dispatched.  And then, there is was.....the Tower of Kurn.  Birthplace of the wretched Sarnak and the home to the Burynai Legion.<br>
<br>
Drakhnar and Elder Trassk entered the tower after asscending an unusually long ramp.  The inside was dark, and the scent of dust, mold and death itself slammed into drakhnar like a wall, almost toppleing him as it burned his nostrils.  Trassk was not so effected by this and on seeing his compainion keep his composure, Drakhnar quickly stood to full height and signalled to the Elder that he was ready to continue.  Trassk reached into his belt pouch and pulled forth a few small bone chips.  He threw them on the ground before himself and quickly chanted a spell.  A number of bones that were lying in the corner began to pull themselves together, centering on the few chips the old lizard had thrown on the ground.   Within seconds the skelletal form of a long dead Iksar had formed and was standing before it's new master.  Drakhnar followed suit and did the same.  <br>
<br>
The group proceeded deeper into Kurn's Tower.  Almost immediatly they were set uppon by a trio of &quot;unfriendly&quot; undead.  And almost as quickly those 3 were dispatched, the fragments of their bones were then gathered and deposited in Drakhnar's pack for use in the creation of future pets. Trassk turned to Drakhnar and spoke for the first time since they had set out on this mission.  &quot;Young one&quot; his voice rasped, &quot;I am here for one thing only.  You can have anything elsssse we come accrossssss.  Onsse we find that thing I sssearch for, we will be done here.&quot;  <br>
<br>
Deeper they went.  As they continued, the enemies that set uppon them appeared to become much stronger.  Soon they found themselves pitted against forces equal to their own.  But Elder Trassk pushed forth, and Drakhnar, bound by his oaths to the order, followed.  Onward they went, until the old lizard suddenly stopped.  A disturbed look passed over his face as he stared into the darkened corner of a room.  Drakhnar was about to ask what was wrong, but changed his mind and followed Trassk's gaze to see what the old one saw.  And there, in the corner, were the half rotted remains of what appeared to be another necromancer.  Trassk began to move forward to the corpse, and Drahnar began to follow, but was stopped short by the scaly outstreched hand of the old lizard, motioning for Drakhnar to wait where he was.  &quot;This must be it&quot; Drakhnar thought to himself.  <br>
<br>
As the old lizard approached the corpse, something out of the corner of his eye caught drakhnar's attention.  Quickly he turned to look, and found himself staring at the face of a Burynai necromancer who was beginning to weave a spell.  Rage spread over drakhnars face as he realized what the Burynai was trying to do.  &quot;NO!&quot; he shouted, motioning for his skelletal pet to attack the furry beast.  The Burynai must not have seen Drakhnar because the expression that covered his furry face could only be described as shock.  However, the foul creature managed to finish casting his spell before Drakhnar's pet could reach him.  Drakhnar heard Trassk hiss as the corpse of the fallen necro began to stir.  That hiss was then quickly turned into a gurggline howl of pain as the now animated corpse plunged a bone dagger into the old lizards chest.  Trassk reeled as his pet set uppon the walking dead.  Drakhnar quickly turned his attention to the furry beast which had caused this.  And with hate and rage unlike anything he felt before, he utterly destroyed his enemy, quickly turning his attention to the now animated dead and dispatching it with the combined power of he and the elder necro.  <br>
<br>
Slowly the old necro walked over to the again dead corpse.  It was obviuos he was in great pain.  With agonizing slowness Trassk bent down to pick up an old dusty tome.  Carefully he examined it and with a sigh, placed it in his pack.  Slowly he turned to walk towards the door, but instead his legs buckled and he fell to the floor.  Drakhnar tried to help him to his feet, but the old lizard pushed him away.  Instead, Trassk reached back into his pack and withdrew the tome he had just placed in there.   Slowly he pressed it into Drakhnar's hands and said &quot;Thisss I give to you.  Pleassse return it to our order.  If you mussst know about it, pleassse asssk one of the massstersss.  They will tell you.&quot;   Trassk then grasped the amulet around his neck and gave it a tug.  The tug was not hard, but it was enough to free it's bindings and make it fall free.  Trassk also pressed this into Drakhnar's hands and spoke.  &quot;You probably do not know thissss, but you are my ssson.  A broodling isss never told of hisss true parents because they are sssupposssed to think themssselvesss a child of the Iksssar rasssse.  However I have followed you in your life none-the-lesssss. And I am proud of you.  But there issss more to do.   That amulet will unlock my journal.  In it you will find the quesssstsss I have been on.  To you I leave all my belongingsssss.  If othersss challenge thisss, jussst sssshow them the amulet.&quot;   His chest heaving painfully, Trassk's voice began to waver, &quot;Go now.  It isss not sssafe for you here and you mussst get out before the Burynai'ssss friendsss come looking for him.&quot;   And with that, Trassk's chest heaved one last time expelling the very life from his body.<br>
<br>
Drakhnar stood in shock.  He was dumbfounded.  In a daze he made his way to the exit of Kurn's Tower and headed for Cabilis.  Even though his mind was flooding with the words that Trassk...his father, had told him, but he was also very curious about the contents of this ancient tome.  His curiosity piqued, he decided to find himself a place where he could examine the book in solitude.  <br>
<br>
Drakhnar wandered for a good hour until he found an abandoned crypt of some kind to the north of Cabilis.  There he sat in a corner and began to read the book, the only ilumination he had was the warm glow of a fire beetle's eye that he had brought with him.  He cracked the book open and began to look over the first page.  He was perplexed by the book's contents.  It read, not like a book, but rather like something that was meant to be spoken aloud.   Like a flash of lighting in the midnight sky realization spread across his face.  This was no ordinary tome.  This was a book of spells, researched by that necromancer!  Quickly he fumbled in his own pack and withdrew his own spellbook.  Hastily he began to transcribe the spells so that he could study them more in detail later.<br>
<br>
For two days Drakhnar wrote.  He was oblivious to the time or even what was going on outside of the crypt....his crypt.  He liked this place and thought it would make an excellent &quot;get away&quot;.  Finaly though, he was done.  Carefully he placed both books back in his packs and stood.  He had learned a new spell from the book he found.  The original author had called it &quot;gate&quot; and the description of it's use was something that Drakhnar thought he would find very helpfull so he had memorized it.  Quietly he chanted the words, and vanished into nothingness.  Everything went black.  For a moment he paniced, thinking he had somehow horribly messed up.  Then with a fluid ripping sound his world was once again filled with light and sound.  Drakhnar looked around, only to see the gazes of a few surprised guards who's group he suddenly appeared in the middle of.  Drakhnar, realizing where he was, bowed to the guards and headed for the entrance of Cabilis propper.  He had to return this old book to his masters, now that he was done with it that is.<br>
<br>
Drakhnar sat in his father's house.  It was not a big house, in fact, it was more like a one room shack built out of the ruins of a once magnificent building.  The care the ancient carpenter took in fasioning the very floorboards together was all but obscured in decades, if not centuries of dust and dirt.  Drakhnar sat and stared at his father's trunk.  He was hesitant to open it thinking that it's owner would return to claim it, though he knew this would never happen.  Drakhner reached up to the amulet now tied around his neck, and pulled it free.  Gingerly he placed it in the slot that it obviously was meant to fit in.  Nothing happened.  Puzzled, he looked at the lock and tried to figure out if it was rusted closed or something, but it was not.   Drakhnar then tried to turn the amulet to the right.  Still nothing.  Then he tried the left.  While he was turning, he pressed down on the amulet, and felt a sharp click.  Fearing he had somehow broken it, it quickly withdrew his hand only to see the lid spring up a few inches.  Carefully he retreived the amulet from it's place in the lock and began to look through his fathers things.  Among them were many differnt ancient and powerful artifacts as well as a number of different clothing items.  Drakhnar realized the wealth of his find and promptly discarded many of his items in exchange for these new ones.  And at the bottom of the trunk he found a locked book.  A book with a lock that was exactly the same as the one he found on the trunk itself.  Carefully he removed it from the trunk and opened it with he key.  There he sat, reading over his father's words.  <br>
<br>
Drakhnar's masters and teachers were beginning to worry about him.  They had not seen him in the last week and he had not showed up for any training recently.  They decided to find out what had happened and dispatched Elder Marsyk to find him.  They knew he was in the city somewhere, but they did not know where.  For three more days Marsyk searched.  He was about to give up and return to his masters when he got word of reculsive individual seen going in and out of the tunnels below the city.  He decided to investigate.  For another day he searched the tunnels.  Finaly he came across what looked to be a camp of some sort.  It seemed to be empty but the coals from the fire were still glowing and there were supplies gathered around.  The occupant would be back, and he would wait.<br>
<br>
Drakhnar had needed some more pieces of parchment.  He still had so much research to do.  Absentmindedly he wove his way through the long forgotten tunnels.   Only to suddenly stop short when he heard the crackleing of a fire.  He knew he had put the fire out before he had left and immediately became suspicious.  Carefully he withdrew his dagger and prepared himself to cast some of his newfound spells only to sigh a breath of releif when he saw his old teacher prodding the coals of the thought dead fire back to roaring life.  Elder Marsyk grinned at his student and said &quot;There you are young Drakhnar.  Tell me, why do you hide in these forgotten passssagewayssss?&quot;  Drakhnar grinned at his old friend and replied, &quot;I know who my father wassss.  He left me hissss possssessssionssss and I have been trying to learn all that he knew.&quot;   Marsyk leaned back and said &quot;Learning issss good, but you have not been to training for quite sssome time.  The Massssterssss are becoming conssserned.&quot;   Drakhnar sat across the fire, staring at it blankly, noticably deep in thought.  He breathed in sharply, then paused as if the words were hanging on his lips.  &quot;Yessss?&quot; Marsyk said.  Again Drakhnar paused, but quickly continued &quot;Teacher, I feel it is time for me to move on.&quot;   Marsyk, not seeming to be a bit surprised, replied, &quot;Young Drakhnar, you have much to learn, but I knew thisss day would sssoon come.  If you wish, I will return to the Massstersss and tell them you will be journying on your own for a while.&quot;  Drakhnar thought for minute then replied &quot;Thank you teacher.  I will probably be leaving for Antonica, asssssss the ssssoft sssskinsss call it, rather early in the morning.&quot;   Elder Marsyk chuckled, &quot;Be carefull.  You are but a broodling yet and there are many dangerssss in the world.   Mossst rasssesss do not like usss and will kill ussss, any of usssss, if they get the chance.   Keep thisss in mind.  Ssssoft ssskinsss are not to be trusted, but if you musst ssseek out alliesss, find the onesss called Dark Elvesss.&quot;  And with that Elder Marsyk stood, bowed and left.<br>
<br>
The next morning Drakhnar began his journys across Norrath. <p></p><i></i></td></tr></table><table border=0 width=95%><tr><td align=left valign="top"> </td><td align=right valign="top"><a href="http://pub42.ezboard.com/fayonaerofrm10.showPrevMessage?topicID=4.topic"> << Prev Topic</a>&nbsp;| <a href="http://pub42.ezboard.com/fayonaerofrm10.showNextMessage?topicID=4.topic"> Next Topic >> </a><br><br><a self href=http://pub42.ezboard.com/fayonaerofrm10.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=4.topic&index=3><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/themes/grunge/addReply.jpg border=0 alt="Add Reply"></a> </td></tr></table><br><table width=95% border=0><td valign="top"> <a href=http://pub42.ezboard.com/fayonaerofrm10.emailToFriend?topicID=4.topic><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/image/email.gif border=0 alt="Email This To a Friend"> Email This To a Friend</a><br> <a href=http://pub42.ezboard.com/fayonaerofrm10.threadControl?topicID=4.topic><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/themes/grunge/deleteThread.gif border=0 alt="Topic Control Image"> Topic Commands (Moderator only)</a><br> <a href=http://pub42.ezboard.com/fayonaerofrm10.subscribeUnregisteredToTopic?topicID=4.topic>Subscribe</a> Click to receive email notification of replies<br>  <a href=http://pub42.ezboard.com/fayonaerofrm10.unsubscribeUnregisteredToTopic?topicID=4.topic>Unsubscribe</a> Click to stop receiving email notification of replies<br> </td><td align="right" valign="top"></td></tr><tr align="right"><td colspan=2><form action=http://pub42.ezboard.com/BBSForum.jumpShowForum method=post><table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="1"><tr><td><b>jump to:</b><select name=forumName><option value="ayonaerofrm1">General Forum<option value="ayonaerofrm6">NAG (Nearly Anything Goes)<option value="ayonaerofrm7">The Bazaar<option value="ayonaerofrm12">Nuggets<option value="ayonaerofrm14">Guilds<option value="ayonaerofrm8">Raid Forum<option value="ayonaerofrm9">Polls, Tests & Beyond